  "prompt": "Orchestral Music: In a classical concert why does the soloist stand next to the conductor and hardly look at him/her?",
  "response": "In an orchestral performance, the soloist typically stands next to the conductor (often slightly off to one side) for several reasons:\n\n1. Visibility and Communication\n- The soloist needs to be visible to the audience\n- They can see the conductor peripherally to stay synchronized with the orchestra\n- They can hear the orchestral accompaniment clearly\n\n2. Musical Coordination\n- While it might seem like they're not looking directly at the conductor, experienced soloists are actually very attuned to the conductor's movements and cues\n- They use peripheral vision and their musical training to stay coordinated\n- Subtle gestures from the conductor can indicate tempo, dynamics, and entry points\n\n3. Performance Tradition\n- This positioning has been a standard in classical music performance for centuries\n- It allows for a natural stage presence and theatrical positioning\n\n4. Mutual Respect\n- The positioning suggests a collaborative relationship between soloist and conductor\n- It implies the soloist is a featured artist, not simply being directed\n\n5. Practical Acoustics\n- This position often provides the best acoustic balance between soloist and orchestra\n\nThe seemingly casual stance actually involves very precise musical communication and is the result of years of training and performance practice.",
